                <div class="col-md-8 col-sm-12 col-xs-12">

                    
                        
                        <div class="author-byline" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
                                <div class="author-headshot">
                    <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/author/34-bob-pockrass">
                    <div class="headshot"><img src="http://st.snimg.com/image/writer/bob-pockrass-40-50.jpg" itemprop="image" alt="A headshot of Bob Pockrass"></div>
                    </a>

                </div>
                
                <div class="author-name">
                    <div>
                      By <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/author/34-bob-pockrass"><span itemprop="name">Bob Pockrass</span></a>
                      <div class="contributor-tag"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>


                
            </div>
        
    

                        <div class="dateline">
        Published on Sep. 19, 2014    </div>

                    <div class="content" itemprop="articleBody">
                                                                                    <p>Tony Stewart continues to let the legal process take its course as he tries to go about his business this weekend at New Hampshire Motor Speedway.</p>
<p>Ontario County (N.Y.) District Attorney Mike Tantillo announced Tuesday that he would take <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2014-09-16/tony-stewart-case-headed-to-grand-jury">Stewart's case over the death of sprint-car racer Kevin Ward Jr. to a grand jury.</a> Stewart’s car struck and killed the 20-year-old Ward, who had walked onto the track and approached Stewart’s car as he drove under caution during an Empire Super Sprints race Aug. 9 at Canandaigua Motorsports Park.</p>
<div class="ad-unit-module visible-xs visible-sm"><div id="in-article-ad-4610893-1"
  data-placement-id="SECTION_MOBILE_300x250_ARTICLE"
  data-section="nascar"
  data-page-type="ARTICLE"
  data-parameters="{&quot;kvslug&quot;:&quot;tony-stewart-investigation-grand-jury-criminal-charges-kevin-ward-death-accident-district-attorney&quot;,&quot;kvzone&quot;:&quot;article&quot;,&quot;kvhas_video&quot;:0,&quot;kvarticleid&quot;:&quot;4610893&quot;,&quot;kvstory_sport&quot;:&quot;nascar&quot;,&quot;kvdart_ad&quot;:&quot;nascar\/story&quot;}"
  data-min-height="250"
  data-margin-bottom="24px"
  data-load-in-view="true"
  data-load="true">
</div></div><p><strong>MORE: <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2014-09-17/tony-stewart-investigation-grand-jury-evidence-testimony-prosecutor-kevin-ward-death">Things to know about grand jury</a> | <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2014-09-17/tony-stewart-investigation-suspension-grand-jury-kevin-ward-death-accident-nfl-ray-rice-adrian-peterson">Should Stewart be suspended?</a> | <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2014-09-19/jimmie-johnson-chase-standings-start-2014-season-struggles-new-hampshire">Jimmie Johnson struggles</a> | <a href="http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2014-09-18/new-hampshire-loudon-picks-predictions-chase-brad-keselowski-kyle-busch-jeff-gor">N.H. picks</a></strong></p>
<p>The three-time Cup champion has pledged his cooperation.</p>
<p>“I respect the time and effort spent by both the Ontario County District Attorney and the Sheriff’s Office in investigating this tragic accident,” Stewart said in a statement Tuesday. “I look forward to this process being completed, and I will continue to provide my full cooperation.” </p>
<p>“The only concern I have is that it sounds like there’s a second tape they haven’t released and I don’t understand why,” Sprint Cup driver Brad Keselowski said Friday. “Beyond that, it kind of feels a little bit like a cop out that they sent it to the grand jury.</p>
<p>“I think everybody is wishing Tony the best and supporting him and that’s probably the most important thing.”</p>
<p>The grand jury will decide if there is enough evidence to charge (the grand jury does not determine guilt) Stewart with a crime. The district attorney presents evidence and details the charges that could be applicable, and the grand jury decides whether to indict on those charges, a lesser charge or no charges at all. The most likely charge, if any, in this case would be criminal negligence while a second-degree manslaughter charge is not out of the question.</p>
<p>Without knowing the evidence — the sheriff’s office has declined to release any documents or video from its investigation because the district attorney considers it an active investigation — there is no concrete way to know why Tantillo is taking the case to the grand jury.</p>
<p>According to the district attorney’s ethical handbook for New York, “as a prosecutor, you are specifically forbidden to institute, cause to be instituted or maintain a criminal charge when (you) know or it is obvious that the charge is not supported by probable cause.”</p>
<p>So if it was obvious Stewart should not be charged, the prosecutor is not supposed to take it to a grand jury. But it is not unheard of for a prosecutor, who is an elected official, to use the grand jury to determine charges so the prosecutor isn’t the sole person responsible for the decision, especially when the decision in a highly publicized case is not to prosecute.</p>
<p>There is no timetable for any decision to be announced by the district attorney.</p>
<p>“I think the whole industry and the world is waiting to see when Tony is able to sit at a mic and talk,” six-time Cup champion Jimmie Johnson said Friday. “So, I’m like all of you; I’m just waiting.”</p>
